  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Advancing Resilience and Early Recovery: Provision of Agricultural Inputs to Vulnerable Farmers in Dara&#x2019;a</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Syria Relief and Development (SRD) will enhance the resilience of 300 small to medium scale farmers in Dara&#x2019;a governorate through provision of agricultural inputs, integrated nutrition messaging and technical agricultural trainings that will facilitate sustainable restoration of annual and seasonal farming activities. This intervention will complement an initiative funded by Near East Foundation (NEF) with a projected start date in September 2017 and will prioritize  assets in the form of seeds and fertilizer that will support crop production among farmers that retain at least 2-5 Dunams (0.2-0.5 Hectares) and demonstrate need for external support to reinvigorate farming activities. Such prioritization was based on a preliminary assessment SRD conducted with five farmers in Tafas, Dar&#x2019;a. SRD is launching an existing food security project in South Syria to provide multi-year assistance encompassing distribution of agricultural inputs to medium-scale farmers in the form of seeds, fertilizer and tools. This program will also entail: market assessments, value chain analysis (agricultural inputs), producers and processors of agricultural inputs are beneficiaries in S. Syria, agribusiness plan development for producers, business incubators (Siraj livelihood hubs) for business trainings, value chain cooperative (co-op), and sales channels established for producers and processors (i.e. community level, regional level, wholesale agreements). 
The proposed HPF intervention will  include  supplementary inputs to the  targeted farmers to ensure that they have the full range of resources necessary for production. The cross-border Food Security and Livelihoods working group in Jordan estimates a standardized minimum response package of seeds, wheat and potatoes alone to cost around 150 to 200 USD. The additional inputs are essential to make a sustainable impact and maximize efficient management of resources, and mitigate the risk of reselling inputs due to lack of sufficient resources, as well as negative coping mechanisms adopted due to limited income that place all gender and age groups in danger of various protection risks. Technical trainings will also be delivered on agricultural best practices, quality control and climate smart techniques.</narrative>
  </description>
